🌐 Same-Origin Policy (SOP), CORS & CSRF
Module: Web Security
Lesson: Day 9

Introduction
Modern web browsers are responsible for protecting users from malicious websites.

Imagine you are logged into:

https://bank.com
If you later visit:

https://evil.com
Without browser security, evil.com could read your bank account details, messages, and personal information.

To prevent this, browsers implement several security mechanisms:

Same-Origin Policy (SOP)
Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS)
CSRF Protection
Although these concepts are related, they solve different security problems.

What is an Origin?
An Origin is made up of three components:

Protocol
Domain (Hostname)
Port
Example:

https://example.com:443
Origin consists of:

Protocol → https
Domain → example.com
Port → 443
All three together uniquely identify an origin.

Same Origin Examples
URL 1	URL 2	Same Origin?	Reason
https://example.com	https://example.com	✅ Yes	Everything matches
https://example.com	http://example.com	❌ No	Protocol changed
https://example.com	https://admin.example.com	❌ No	Domain changed
https://example.com	https://example.com:8080	❌ No	Port changed
Remember:

If Protocol, Domain, or Port changes, the origin changes.

What is Same-Origin Policy (SOP)?
Same-Origin Policy (SOP) is a browser security policy.

It prevents JavaScript running on one origin from reading data belonging to another origin.

Its purpose is to protect users from malicious websites trying to steal sensitive information.

Example
Suppose you are logged into:

https://bank.com
You then visit:

https://evil.com
evil.com tries to read:

https://bank.com/account
Browser:

❌ Access Denied
The browser blocks JavaScript from reading the response.

Important Point
SOP does not always stop requests from being sent.

It mainly prevents JavaScript from reading the response returned by another origin.

This is one of the most misunderstood concepts in web security.

SOP Flow
User

↓

Visits bank.com

↓

Logs In

↓

Visits evil.com

↓

evil.com Attempts to Read bank.com

↓

Browser Blocks Response

↓

Sensitive Data Protected
Same-Origin Access
Requests within the same origin are allowed.

Example:

https://example.com

↓

Reads

↓

https://example.com/profile

↓

Allowed
Cross-Origin Access
Different origins are restricted.

Example:

https://evil.com

↓

Reads

↓

https://bank.com/account

↓

Blocked
Why Do We Need CORS?
Many modern websites separate the frontend and backend.

Example:

Frontend:

https://app.example.com
Backend API:

https://api.example.com
Different subdomains mean different origins.

Without CORS, the frontend would not be able to access its own backend API.

What is CORS?
CORS stands for:

Cross-Origin Resource Sharing

It is a mechanism that allows the server to tell the browser:

"This origin is allowed to access my resources."

CORS does not disable SOP.

Instead, it provides controlled exceptions.

CORS Flow
Frontend

↓

Cross-Origin Request

↓

Browser Checks CORS

↓

Server Sends Permission

↓

Browser Allows Response
Important CORS Header
Access-Control-Allow-Origin:
https://app.example.com
This tells the browser:

Only https://app.example.com may read the response.

Other Common CORS Headers
Allowed Methods
Access-Control-Allow-Methods:
GET, POST, PUT
Specifies which HTTP methods are allowed.

Allowed Headers
Access-Control-Allow-Headers:
Authorization, Content-Type
Specifies which request headers are permitted.

Allow Credentials
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:
true
Allows cookies or authentication credentials to be included in cross-origin requests.

Preflight Request
Some cross-origin requests are considered "non-simple."

Before sending the actual request, the browser first sends an OPTIONS request.

Purpose:

Ask the server:

"Is this request allowed?"

Preflight Flow
Browser

↓

OPTIONS Request

↓

Server

↓

Allowed?

↓

200 OK

↓

Real Request Sent
Example
Browser:

OPTIONS /users HTTP/1.1

Origin: https://app.example.com

Access-Control-Request-Method: PUT
Server:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Access-Control-Allow-Origin:
https://app.example.com

Access-Control-Allow-Methods:
PUT
The browser then sends the actual PUT request.

Common CORS Misconfigurations
Wildcard Origin
Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
Means:

Every origin is allowed.

This is acceptable for public resources, but dangerous for authenticated or sensitive APIs.

Credentials with Arbitrary Origins
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
If combined with a server that trusts arbitrary origins (for example, by reflecting the Origin header), sensitive authenticated data may become accessible to attacker-controlled websites.

Browsers intentionally reject the combination of:

Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
because it would be unsafe.

What is CSRF?
CSRF stands for:

Cross-Site Request Forgery

It is an attack that tricks a logged-in user's browser into sending unwanted requests.

Unlike SOP or CORS, CSRF is an attack, not a browser security policy.

Example
Victim logs into:

https://bank.com
Browser stores:

session=abc123
Victim later visits:

https://evil.com
The attacker secretly submits:

<form action="https://bank.com/transfer" method="POST">

<input type="hidden" name="amount" value="1000">

<input type="hidden" name="to" value="attacker">

</form>

<script>

document.forms[0].submit();

</script>
The browser automatically sends:

Cookie:
session=abc123
The bank believes the request came from the legitimate user.

Why Does CSRF Work?
Browsers automatically include:

Session Cookies
Authentication Cookies
The server sees:

Valid Session
Authenticated User
If no additional protection exists, the action succeeds.

CSRF Token
The most common defense against CSRF.

The server generates a unique, random token.

Example:

<input

type="hidden"

name="csrf_token"

value="XyZ98AB12">
When the form is submitted:

Server checks:

Does the token exist?
Does it match the user's session?
If not:

403 Forbidden
The request is rejected.

SameSite Cookies
SameSite is another defense against CSRF.

Example:

Set-Cookie:

session=abc123;

SameSite=Lax
Available values:

Strict
Cookies are sent only during same-site navigation.

Highest protection.

Lax
Cookies are sent for most normal navigation.

Balances usability and security.

Most browsers use this by default.

None
Cookies are always sent.

Must be combined with:

Secure
SOP vs CORS vs CSRF
Feature	Purpose
SOP	Prevents JavaScript from reading cross-origin responses
CORS	Allows selected origins to bypass SOP
CSRF	Tricks authenticated users into sending unwanted requests
Real Burp Suite Example
Request:

GET /api/profile HTTP/1.1

Origin: https://evil.com

Cookie: session=abc123
Response:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK

Access-Control-Allow-Origin:
https://evil.com

Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:
true
Questions:

Why is evil.com trusted?
Is the server reflecting arbitrary origins?
Can authenticated data now be read by an attacker-controlled site?
Pentester's Perspective 🔍
Whenever you test a web application, ask yourself:

SOP
Can browser protections be bypassed?
Is sensitive data accidentally exposed?
CORS
Is Access-Control-Allow-Origin set to *?
Does the server reflect the Origin header?
Are credentials allowed?
Can authenticated data be read by another origin?
CSRF
Is a CSRF token required?
Is the token random and validated?
Are Origin or Referer headers checked?
Is SameSite configured?
Can state-changing actions be performed without additional verification?
Interview Questions
What is an Origin?
An Origin consists of:

Protocol
Domain
Port
What is Same-Origin Policy?
SOP is a browser security policy that prevents JavaScript from reading responses from different origins.

What is CORS?
CORS is a server-controlled mechanism that allows specific origins to access cross-origin resources.

What is a Preflight Request?
A Preflight Request is an OPTIONS request sent by the browser before certain cross-origin requests to check whether the server permits the request.

What is CSRF?
CSRF is an attack that tricks an authenticated user's browser into sending unwanted requests to another website.

How do CSRF Tokens work?
The server generates a unique token and includes it in requests. When the request is submitted, the server verifies the token. If it is missing or incorrect, the request is rejected.

How does SameSite help?
SameSite controls when cookies are sent during cross-site requests, reducing the risk of CSRF attacks.

